## Edit-lock lease — auto-expire abandoned locks (renew-only, no unload-release)

### Context

The single-editor DRAFT lock had **no auto-expiry**: a crashed browser or a tab
closed without hitting **Close** held the lock forever, recoverable only by an
admin force-unlock (Settings › Locks) or take-over. Requested: a lease so
abandoned locks free themselves. The earlier heartbeat model was removed
precisely because it *released on unload*, and a multi-page app unloads on every
navigation — so the lock got stolen mid-session. This adds a **renew-only
lease**: the lock is never released on unload; it only lapses when the holder
stops renewing for a full TTL, at which point the next opener silently reclaims
it. Reuses the long-dormant `heartbeat_at` column as the lease clock (no
migration). Config: `ONTOBRICKS_EDIT_LOCK_TTL_S` (seconds, default `600`; `0`
disables the lease → prior hold-until-close behaviour).

### Changes

1. `src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py`
   - `acquire_edit_lock(..., ttl_seconds=0)`: `ON CONFLICT` now also grants when
     the current lease is **stale** (`ttl > 0 AND now() - heartbeat_at >
     make_interval(secs => ttl)`). Bumps `heartbeat_at = now()` on every grant;
     resets `acquired_at` only when the holder actually changes (a same-holder
     refresh keeps the original session start via a `CASE`).
   - New `renew_edit_lock(folder, version, *, holder_email)` → `UPDATE
     heartbeat_at = now()` iff the caller still holds it; `False` = lease lost.
   - `get_edit_lock(..., ttl_seconds=0)` / `_get_edit_lock_row(...)` compute an
     `is_stale` flag server-side and return `heartbeat_at`.
   - `list_all_edit_locks(ttl_seconds=0)` adds `heartbeat_at` + `is_stale` for
     the admin Locks panel.
2. `src/back/objects/registry/EditLockService.py`
   - New `renew(...)` → `{success, renewed}` (DRAFT-gated, holder-scoped).
   - `_ttl_seconds()` reads `ONTOBRICKS_EDIT_LOCK_TTL_S` (default 600, `0`
     disables); threaded into every `acquire_edit_lock` / `get_edit_lock` /
     `list_all_edit_locks` call.
   - `blocking_holder` now treats a **stale** lease as *not blocking*, so the
     `PermissionMiddleware` edit gate never locks a new editor out on an
     abandoned lock.
   - Status/acquire payloads carry `lease_ttl_s` (client renew-cadence hint).
3. `src/api/routers/internal/domain.py`
   - New `POST /domain/edit-lock/renew` → `EditLockService.renew(...)`. (No
     middleware change: it inherits the same treatment as `/edit-lock/acquire`
     and is not status-gated, so it never trips the edit-lock 403 gate.)
4. `src/front/static/global/js/edit-lock.js`
   - While `mode == "edit"` and `lease_ttl_s > 0`, a keep-alive timer pings
     `/domain/edit-lock/renew` every ~TTL/3 (and on tab re-focus). Never
     releases on unload — the timer just dies and the lease lapses naturally.
   - On a lost lease (`renewed === false`) it flips to read-only and shows a
     new **"your editing session expired — read-only, saving disabled"** banner
     with a **Reload** button. Transient network/backend blips are ignored (the
     next tick retries).

### Docs

- `docs/user-guide.md`, `docs/architecture.md`, `docs/features.md`: rewrote the
  single-editor sections from "release-based, no TTL" to the renew-only lease
  (auto-expiry, background renew, `ONTOBRICKS_EDIT_LOCK_TTL_S`, expired banner,
  stale-lease handling in the gate + admin panel).

### Tests

- `tests/units/registry/test_edit_lock_store.py`: TTL reclaim clause + params,
  `renew_edit_lock` (holder / non-holder), `get_edit_lock` `is_stale` calc +
  stale passthrough, updated `list_all` params to the TTL pair.
- `tests/units/registry/test_edit_lock_service.py`: `renew` (renewed / lost /
  non-DRAFT no-op), `status` exposes `lease_ttl_s` + forwards `ttl_seconds`,
  `blocking_holder` ignores a stale lease.
- `tests/units/api/test_edit_lock_endpoints.py`: `/domain/edit-lock/renew`
  delegation.

